Interview - Blood that is safe again
Hema-Quebec celebrated his tenth anniversary and his president, Dr. Francine Décary, was rightly pleased because Hema-Quebec became one of the most reliable and inefficient blood suppliers in the world.
First of all, he regained the confidence of the public, who was seriously disturbed by the scandal with contaminated blood in the 1980s and 1990s.
As is generally known, the State reserve of blood administered by the Canadian Red Cross Transfusion Committee was contaminated by an immunodeficiency (HIV) virus and a hepatitis C virus during the 1980s.
In February 1994, the Canadian government launched a public investigation by Judge Horace Krever, which was intended to explain the circumstances leading to such a tragedy, and to make recommendations that such a massacre should not be repeated.
While Judge Krever stopped reporting, some provinces set up a committee to plan a new blood management system in Canada.
In Quebec, Géline's committee was set up.
After Gélineau and Krever's report, two suppliers were established in Canada: Hema-Québec, which was to operate Quebec, and the Canadian blood company for the supply of all provinces and both territories.
"When Hema-Québec began its activities in 1998, almost 38% of people still had confidence in the Québec blood system," recalls Dr. Décary.
"The situation was exciting.
In a systematic effort to increase the safety of blood products and the continued work in this area over the next years, we have regained public confidence," he says and proudly adds that in early 2008 Hema-Québec believed almost 94% of the Quebec population.
However, Dr. Décary does not lose sight of the fact that "faith is something very fragile".
Since its establishment on 28 September 1998, Hema-Québec has applied the principle of caution.
"At that time we have witnessed in Europe the occurrence of many cases of a human form of the disease of crazy cows, new variants of the disease called Creutzfeldt-Jakob's disease," says a woman who has been leading the company since her founding in 1998.
"And we didn't know if this disease could spread with blood.
We therefore relied on one of the basic recommendations of Krever and Gélineau's report, according to which, in the event that we do not know, and when serious disease is being spread, in this case Creutzfeldt-Jakob's disease, which is characterized by the degeneration of the brain inevitably leading to death, it is necessary to take exclusive measures.
So in April 1999, we refused blood from people who have stayed in the United Kingdom for more than a month since 1980.
A few years ago, this disease was safely proved to be passed on to blood.
So this episode showed us that keeping the principle of caution made sense."
In 1999 a much more accurate technology for detecting HIV virus was developed on the market: tests using nucleic acid (NAT) that enable donor blood to detect the presence of the virus itself directly, and not the presence of antibodies on which previously used tests were based.
NAT tests have been able to reduce the deafness of the time between the patient’s infection and the moment our first viruses can be detected in the blood, explains the specialist.
We've been able to shorten this period for less than a week.
We have significantly reduced the risk that some donors might be infected without knowing about it and without us being able to figure it out.
This improvement has made it possible to significantly reduce the risk of getting AIDS through blood transfusions.
The risk of getting blood contaminated with HIV is one of the 12 million people exposed today.
"In other words, it means that before someone is infected with HIV, 12 million blood products will have to be distributed.
As a result, Hema-Québec distributes 400,000 to 500,000 blood products every year, it will take 24 years before the first case of HIV transmission occurs through the blood product.
I believe that we can get or prescribe blood transfusions that are necessary for recovery today in complete peace," Hema-Québec, head of management, says.
"The challenge for the next decade is to keep our products safe.
We never know what pathogen can appear in the system.
Just last year, on the island of Réunion, the Chikungunya virus appeared, which is similar to the West Nile virus that is transmitted to the blood by puncture.
It is necessary to be constantly vigilant," continues Dr. Décary and stresses that, in addition to safe supplies, Hema-Québec must also be counted with sufficient supplies.
"They need to grow, because the population is getting older.
As a result of more aggressive treatment of cancer, patients often need a new dose of red blood cells or platelets.
The ageing population also has consequences for the network of blood donors, which averages only 3% of Quebecans eligible to donate."
Every healthy person is at least 18 years old, meeting the eligibility criteria, but can donate blood only once in 56 days, which means six times a year.
14% of people offering blood are not accepted on average because, for example, they are carriers of AIDS or malaria, and if they visited the country where the cold is taking place, they are excluded for a period of one year.
"With these 3%, we can maintain a state that meets the needs of hospitals.
The deficiencies are very rare.
However, the members of the donor network should be adequately complemented by how old they are and are no longer able to donate blood.
But to convince people to give blood is difficult, especially to keep and encourage them to become regular donors.
Life today is so inconvenient that we can only find an hour to donate blood," Francine Décary says.
With an annual budget of $297 million, Hema-Québec supplies not only blood products, but also human tissue, such as bone transplants, heart valves, eye bubbles and skin, which is almost exclusively used for large burns.
These tissues are analysed, processed and frozen before being stored at Hema-Quebek, which also manages the only public blood bank from the Québec poppy line.
The umbilical cord, previously considered biomedical waste, pours blood rich into stem cells that can be used to treat serious diseases, such as leukemia.
"A few weeks ago, we celebrated the contribution of our thousands of blood samples from the umbilical cord to the bank and we assume that we will take them back over a thousand years.
At the beginning of next year, we should start offering them for transplants," explains Dr. Décary, who describes the blood collection program as very popular.
"Some mothers are disappointed that they do not have access to it," because Hema-Québec does not have enough resources to offer this comprehensive and expensive program to all hospitals in Quebec.
