The process of limiting cinemas, the production of large multisalts in the suburbs and the subsequent collapse of monosalts in the central areas of cities is one of the events that seem inevitable and irreversible, but also has all the signs of a real cultural crime.
Often the historical places are filled with memories," it is as if we had lost a friend, a friend with whom we shared a piece of road and a lot of emotion," says the director of the New Cinema Paradiso, a film that was won by Tornator Oscar 20 years ago and a great jury price in Cannes, who told the poetry of a village cinema and the sadness of the way of life that the cinema lost forever.
The values obtained by Anek, the main association of operators, are clear: in the last five years, 316 cinemas of traditional type have been closed, and the highest account has been paid mainly to halls in the most important cities: 10 min in Florence, 9 in Milan, Naples, Bologna and Rome, 6 min in Turin, 5 in Palermo.
Among the regions most affected are Emilia-Romagna, with the loss of 82 cinemas followed by Tuscany (44) and Lombardy (41).
And by proving that the first responsible for their mediation is the introduction of multiplex, these three Italian regions have recorded the highest number of new cinemas: 195 more in Lombardy in the last five years, 81 both in Tuscany and Emilia-Romagna.
“Italian procedure has developed abnormally” says Paolo Protti, President Anec, “it is useful to create new structures, but it would be necessary to ensure that those already existing survive, because when one movie closes in the city, not all its visitors are willing to move to multiplex.
Then we do not even talk about insufficient funding for operators: the previous state debt is about EUR 10 million.
From a moral and ethical point of view, it is a shame that the government does not respect existing laws.
In support of the sector, between EUR 16 million and EUR 18 million would be needed annually.’
An interesting case is the Bologna case, the first Italian town to worry about closures and which decided to find the east sign of the protocol between the municipalities and Anec, the first of this type in Italy to protect and promote small cinemas both in historical centres and in the suburbs.
The planned standards include tax impact steps in favour of operators and benefits for the public in terms of mobility: the spectators will be able to travel to a restricted transport zone and will have special parking prices.
"I like this initiative," said Giuseppe Tornatore, and I hope that other cities will follow the example of the Bologna introduction of other measures".
